  </tgroup>
  </table><para id="eip-340">What we observe is that the cost increases as the firm produces higher quantities of output.  This is pretty intuitive, since producing more output requires greater quantities of inputs, which cost more dollars to acquire.</para><para id="eip-994">What is the origin of these cost figures?  They come from the production function and the factor payments. The discussion of costs in the short run above, <link document="m63679">Costs in the Short Run</link>, was based on the following production function, which is similar to <link target-id="eip-147"/> except for "widgets" instead of trees.</para><table id="eip-549" summary="The table indicates the production function for widgets. One worker has a function of 0.2. Two workers has a function of 0.4. Three workers has a function of 0.8. Three point two five has a function of 1. Four point four has a function of 2. Five point two has a function of 3. Six has a function of 3.5. Seven has a function of 3.8. Eight has a function of 3.95. Nine has a function of 4.">
