  </table><para id="eip-480">We can use the information from the production function to determine production costs.  What we need to know is how many workers are required to produce any quantity of output.  If we flip the order of the rows, we “invert” the production function so it shows <m:math><m:mi>L</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>Q</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:math>.</para><table id="eip-353" summary="This table inverts the previous one, so that Widgets (Q) is on top. 0.2 widgets requires 1 worker. 0.4 requires 2 workers . 0.8 widgets requires 3 workers. 1 widget requires 3.25 workers. 2 requires 4.4. 3 widgets require 5.2 workers. 3.5 widgets requires 6 workers. 3.8 requires 7 workers. 3.95 widgets requires 8 workers. And four requires nine workers.">
